<font color="#FF0000">THAT WHICH WAS LOST</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 13 19:29:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br><br>
Art thanks for the clarification on what was lost. You speak of the historical context of warriors and societies mechanism to heal and reverse the effects of combat and to re-integrate the veteran into society.  When you joined the military and went to war had you given any thought to that process at all, or believe there was a historical way to deal with the returning  Vietnam vets? What did you think that contract with society entailed?  Was this the civilian or military society, or something or someone else.  And...who was responsible for seeing this contract was fulfilled?   If no one is designated responsible, whatever it is to be done probably won't ever happen. <br><br>
The historical models I believe you are referring to dealt with warriors meeting a direct threat from outside the immediate community for which the community would then be grateful.  For example, annual ritualized attacks on other tribes and when war parties were less about actual killing (although that might happen) and more about status and counting coup.  I understand the way one indian nation dealt with the returning berzerkers was to send out its women nude to put their minds on other things and remind them they were home.  Sorry fellas....not in this day and age, although the military did a modified version of that by having round-eyed women in the rear.  ( We didn't know that was one of the things we were there for but Sparrowhawk's comments on round eyes alludes to this.)  <br><br>
The rural, agrarian way of dealing with conflict historically has included a clear cut threat to the society for which that society put up with the the  military society for protection.  In our &quot;civilized&quot; world,  the issue of direct threat is not so clear.  There wasn't an enemy on America's shores. We were sent to defend the American way of life but why wasn't a clear defendable position to a large number of the American population.   So, has American society breached its contract, or did we think we had a contract when American society but they didn't think they had one. And even if there was such an animal, who was responsible for seeing the gratitude was extended?   Who the soldiers really had the contract with should have been the South Vietnamese.  But, for a number of reasons things didn't end up working that way.  (Remember the old war clips from WWII when the Allies liberated towns.  It was the people who were liberated that lined the streets praising the warriors.)<br><br>
So were we betrayed because that which was promised wasn't forthcoming? or did we have false expectations from too many John Wayne movies and old WWII warriors who made war a glamorous and glorious endeavor when they came to our classrooms.  Think on these things.<br><br>
From personal experience... I expected no appreciation from the protestors.  They were upfront with their beliefs.  They made no promises of glory for anyone who fought, or went.  I don't blame them for not providing the parades. I wish I had some idea what happened to those other Americans that didn't speak out against the war, said they supported the government, and then kept silent when we came back. <br><br>
Speaking only for myself, for years I  felt betrayed by the men who served in Vietnam, were rejected by the VFW so set they then set up their own organizations only to do the same thing to me because I didn't have a DD214.  For us women, we too were changed by our experiences, we needed to be by your side.  The sound of a car backfiring could send many of us diving for cover.  The whir of helicopter blades stir up strong emotions of incoming wounded.   The nurses had a right for admission, and they could fight for VA benefits.  The rest of us who accompanied the mililtary into the field (Army Special Services, USO, Red Cross) had no status even though we had been subject to the same threats from VC, agent orange, etc.   <br><br>
Tom,<br><br>
You have spoken more eloquently than I can on forgiveness.  Being willing  to forgive is a gift we give ourselves / some higher power outside ourself facilitates.   We choose not to hold onto a hurt or demand retribution even when it is due.  Instead, we choose to let it go. The unwillingness to forget is out of fear that if we forget, it WILL happen again.  Catch me once, shame on you.  Catch me twice, shame on me.  Each person to their own time-frame for cuddling up to the hurt.  The problem is the longer we hang onto whatever the slight, injustice, etc. the more we lose out on other things in life.  When I held onto my hurt from not being allowed to join the VVA except as what I considered a second class citizen (associate membership) I ignored those who did not have grievances against women and would have been willing to let me into the circle. I ignored you all.   I jumped to conclussions without knowing who was and who wasn't my brother.  I now choose,  not to ignor all because of the actions of some and I can forgive those who would abuse me out of their own unresolved pain.  I take the risk of being rejected, expecting the best, but no longer surprized when I get the worst.<br><br>

<p><code>--   (Class Lass) </code><p>


